'''Louis Gordon Rylands''' (July 10, 1862 - December 20, 1942), best known as '''L. Gordon Rylands''' was a British [[criminologist]] and writer.
Rylands was born in [[Warrington|Warrington, Lancashire]]. His father was the politician [[Peter Rylands]].<ref>[http://www.warringtonmuseum.co.uk/blog/the-man-of-philanthropy-politics-and-clogs-circa-1868/ "The Man of Philanthropy, Politics and Clogs"]. Warrington Museum & Art Gallery.</ref> He was educated at [[Charterhouse School|Charterhouse]] and [[University College London]] (B.A., B.Sc). After completing his studies, he was secretary of the family business, Rylands Brothers wire manufacturers from 1884 to 1887, then from 1897 to 1898 was science master at the [[Royal Grammar School, Newcastle upon Tyne]]. He worked as a private tutor from 1898 to 1924. At the time of his death he was assistant registrar of Grimes's Manchester Tutorial College.<ref>Who was Who: A companion to Who's Who, A. & C. Black, 1967, pg 1015</ref> In 1887, he married Katherine Edwards; they had a daughter. Rylands was an uncle of the academic [[Dadie Rylands]].<ref>Who was Who: A companion to Who's Who, A. & C. Black, 1967, pg 1015</ref>
Rylands authored the book ''Crime: Its Causes and Remedy'' (1889).<ref>P. S. R. (1890). [https://www.jstor.org/stable/1321170 Reviewed Work: Crime; Its Nature, Causes, Treatment, and Prevention by Sanford M. Green]. ''[[Harvard Law Review]]'' 3 (8): 383.</ref><ref>[[Roland P. Falkner|Falkner, Roland P]]. (1889). [https://www.jstor.org/stable/2139354 ''Reviewed Works: Penological and Preventive Principles, with Special Reference to Europe and America, etc. by William Tallack; Crime, its Causes and Remedy by L. Gordon Rylands'']. ''[[Political Science Quarterly]]'' 4 (2): 348-350.</ref> Rylands was best known as an advocate of the [[Christ myth theory]]. He denied the historicity of [[Jesus]].<ref>[[Joseph McCabe|McCabe, Joseph]]. (1950). ''A Rationalist Encyclopaedia: A Book of Reference on Religion, Philosophy, Ethics, and Science''. Watts & Co. p. 334. "In England the philosophic writer T. Whittaker, and L. G. Rylands, supported Robertson in denying the historicity of Jesus."</ref><ref>Hawton, Hector. (1971). ''Controversy: The Humanist/Christian Encounter''. Pemberton Books. p. 173</ref>
==Publications== *[https://archive.org/details/crimeitscausesre00rylaiala ''Crime: Its Causes and Remedy''] (1889) *Correspondence and Speeches of Mr. Peter Rylands ([https://archive.org/details/correspondencesp01rylaiala ''Volume 1''], [https://archive.org/details/correspondencesp02rylaiala ''Volume 2''], 1890) *[https://archive.org/details/croesuskingoflyd00rylaiala ''Croesus, King of Lydia: A Drama''] (1902) *''The Evolution of Christianity'' (1927) *[https://archive.org/details/MN41484ucmf_2 ''A Critical Analysis of the Four Chief Pauline Epistles: Romans, First and Second Corinthians, and Galatians]'' (1929) *''Did Jesus Ever Live?'' (1935) *''The Christian Tradition: An Examination of Objections to the Opinion that Jesus Was Not an Historical Person'' (1937) *[https://catalog.hathitrust.org/Record/001410751 ''The Beginnings of Gnostic Christianity''] (1940)<ref>Marcus, Ralph. (1942). [https://www.jstor.org/stable/4464452 ''Reviewed Work: The Beginnings of Gnostic Christianity by L. Gordon Rylands'']. ''Jewish Social Studies'' 4 (2): 172-173.</ref>
